01. Create a table called "students" with columns "id" (integer, primary key, auto-increment), "name" (text), "age" (integer), and "gender" (text).

Answer:
	CREATE TABLE students (
  		id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
  		name TEXT,
  		age INT,
  		gender TEXT
	);	

02. Insert three rows of data into the "students" table.

Answer :
	INSERT INTO students (name, age, gender) VALUES 
	('Uditha Lashan', 28, 'Male'), 
	('Maheshika Dissanayake', 27, 'Female'), 
	('Kasun Kalhara', 35, 'Male');

03. Retrieve all rows from the "students" table.

Answer :
	SELECT * FROM students;
	
04. Update the name of the student with id = 2 to "Janet".

Answer :
	UPDATE students SET students.name="Janet" WHERE id='2';
	
05. Delete the row with id = 3 from the "students" table.

Answer :
	DELETE FROM students WHERE id='3';
	
06. Retrieve all rows from the "students" table again to verify that the changes have been made.

Answer :
	SELECT * FROM students;
	
	id;name;age;gender
	1;Uditha Lashan;28;Male
	2;Janet;27;Female

